Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and attach handlers to all six events:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Created     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("đźź˘ Created");
        window.Activated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("đźź˘ Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("đźźˇ Deactivated");
        window.Stopped     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("đź”´ Stopped");
        window.Resumed     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("đźź˘ Resumed");
        window.Destroying  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("đź’€ Destroying");

        return window;
    }
}
```

**What you'll see in the Output window:**

| Scenario | Events fired |
|---|---|
| App launches | `Created` â†’ `Activated` |
| User switches away | `Deactivated` â†’ `Stopped` |
| User returns | `Resumed` â†’ `Activated` |
| App closed | `Stopped` â†’ `Destroying` |

**Key gotchas:**
- **`Resumed` does not fire on first launch** â€” the initial sequence is only `Created â†’ Activated`.
- **On Android, the back button can skip `Stopped`** and go straight to `Destroying`.
- **`Deactivated` â‰  `Stopped`** â€” a notification shade pull-down fires `Deactivated` but the app never stops.

If you also need the **platform-native** callbacks (e.g., `OnPause`, `DidEnterBackground`), use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` alongside the above.
